Participants will be recruited through the University of Chicago Booth School of 
Business Center for Decision Research participant pool. Because the original study used 
undergraduate students, we will selectively sample undergraduate students. If sampling 
undergraduates does not allow us to reach our target sample size, we will expand the 
sample to include graduate students and MBA students.  
 
Also, because the original study compared European American versus East Asian 
American students, we will selectively recruit participants from these two cultural 
backgrounds. The original study included East Asian participants born abroad but now 
living in the US, as well as East Asian participants born in the US but whose parents were 
born abroad. Thus, we will follow this design, including both US-born and non-US-born 
participants of East Asian backgrounds. 
 
The original authors provided the original materials for the (1) experimental 
manipulation--writing about dental pain or death, (2) the prostitution case description 
that participants read after the writing manipulation, and (3) the attitudes toward 
prostitution scale (PAS) and the bail amount.  
 
We decided to make one change from the original materials. The original study took 
place in Santa Barbara, California, and the prostitution case materials described 
California. Because our participants will be in Chicago, we determined it would be best to 
edit these details to be about Chicago. Of course, deviations in the study materials can 
cause problems. However, research on construal level has found that people respond 
differently when told about situations that are far away as opposed to nearby (Trope & 
Liberman, 2010). Thus, it is plausible that asking participants in Chicago to think about 
California could affect their responses. In order to prevent this, we changed (1) 
references about California to Illinois, (2) references to Santa Barbara to Chicago, (3) 
street names from names common in California (e.g., “Cielo Lane”) to names of streets in 
Chicago (Union and Perry Ave.), (4) references from the original county to Cook County 
(where Chicago is located). For the same reason, we also changed the years recorded in 
the case to 2019 and 2020.  
 
The original authors did not include the original question wordings for the demographic 
questions, so we created these anew. We added these to the end of the study (after 
participants have completed the writing, case, and attitude measures).  
 

 
Trope, Y., and Liberman, N. (2010). Construal level theory of psychological distance. 
Psychological Review​ 117: 440. doi:10.1037/a0018963 
 
  
 
