The main dependent variable is (as described in the original study): ​the Prostitution 
Attitudes Scale (PAS; Rosenblatt et al., 1989), which consists of five items about prostitution (two 
against prostitution and three favoring prostitution); ratings are made on Likert scales ranging 
from −3 (​strongly disagree​) to +3 (​strongly agree​). The two antiprostitution items will be reverse- 
coded (following original study), and ratings for the five items were averaged to yield an overall 
prostitution attitude score, with higher scores reflecting more favorable attitudes toward 
prostitution.  
 
Rosenblatt and colleagues (1989) performed a factor analysis on this scale and found that the 
“factor analysis of this scale revealed only one factor, with all five items loading .70 or higher.” 
The Ma-Kellams study did not report a factor analysis but found that the scale evinced 
satisfactory internal consistency, with a Chrobach’s alpha of 0.74. It is the replicator’s judgment 
that the items show simple face validity.  
 
The original study also asked participants to set a bail amount for prostitution. However, this was 
not the main dependent variable. We will present these analyses in the report, but they are not the 
criterion of replication.
 
 
 
 

 
