For the purposes of SCORE, to test ​H*​ in line with the original paper, [I/we] will use... 
 
The main analysis will be a 2 (condition: mortality salience vs. control priming task) × 2 
(ethnicity: European American vs. Asian American) multivariate ANOVA on the 
dependent variable of the Prostitution Attitudes Scale scores. The original paper found a 
significant interactive effect on PAS (Prostitution Attitudes Scale) score, F(1, 38) = 
10.263, p = .003. 
 
For data checks, we will calculate a Chronbach’s alpha for the PAS. The original study 
found a Chronbach’s alpha of 0.74. We will report the Chronbach’s alpha for the PAS in 
our sample and report the alpha from the published paper so that readers can compare 
the two numbers.  
 
There are different opinions on what alpha values are unacceptable, but ​one source 
suggests values under 0.50 are generally unacceptable. Thus, we will consider an alpha 
of under 0.50 to have unacceptable consistency. Whatever the number, we will report this 
statistic in the paper so that readers will be aware of it. However, we will continue to run 
the statistical interaction test.  
 
To check for outliers, we will produce a histogram of the PAS scores in SPSS. We will 
check for outliers of more than 2 standard deviations on PAS total scores. To follow the 
original, we will run the main statistical interaction test with all participants. However, as 
a robustness check, we will also present the interaction test with > 2 SD outliers removed 
(if any). 
 
Another critical question is the direction of the interaction. Strictly speaking, a significant 
interaction would fit the criterion of a successful replication. However, researchers will 
also be interested in whether the direction of the interaction fits the direction of the 
original study. To break this out, we will (1) produce a figure akin to Figure 1 in the 

 
original article (culture x writing condition on the DV of PAS score) and (2) planned 
statistical comparisons reporting means and t tests. The planned comparisons in the 
original article were reported as follows:  
Planned comparisons showed results consistent with existing TMT research: European 
Americans reported a significantly more negative attitude toward prostitution in the 
mortality-salience condition (​M ​= −0.0092, ​SD ​= 0.28) than in the control condition (​M ​= 
1.022, ​SD ​= 0.34), ​t​(20)= 2.10, ​p ​= .048, whereas Asian Americans showed the opposite 
effect (mortality-salience condition: ​M ​= 0.21, ​SD ​= 0.31; control condition: ​M ​= −0.73, ​SD ​= 
0.34), ​t​(18) = 2.73, ​p ​= .013).  
In other words, for European American participants, mortality salience decreased PAS scores 
compared to the dental pain condition. For East Asian participants, mortality salience increased 
PAS scores compared to the dental pain condition. 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
